Project Description¶

Dataset Chosen for this project: MNIST Dataset (https://www.kaggle.com/competitions/digit-recognizer/data)

In this project, I will try to develop a classifier that can most accurately identify digits in the MNIST dataset. In order to find the best model, I will try to develop and evaluate various models such as SVC, Random Forest, KNN and GaussianNB, and make use of hyperparamater optimization using grid search and PCA to optimize model performances.

The MNIST dataset is a widely used benchmark dataset in the field of machine learning and computer vision. It consists of a set of 70,000 handwritten digits (0-9) that have been normalized and centered in a fixed-size image format of 28x28 pixels. The dataset is split into two subsets: 60,000 images for training and 10,000 images for testing.

Due to its popularity and widespread use, the MNIST dataset has become a standard reference dataset for researchers in the field of machine learning and computer vision. It has also been used as a basis for developing and testing new algorithms and techniques for image recognition, classification, and other related applications.

Data Analysis & Visualization¶

Each image is 28 pixels in height and 28 pixels in width, for a total of 784 pixels in total. Each pixel has a single pixel-value associated with it, indicating the lightness or darkness of that pixel, with higher numbers meaning darker. This pixel-value is an integer between 0 and 255, inclusive.

The training data set, (train.csv), has 785 columns. The first column, called "label", is the digit that was drawn by the user. The rest of the columns contain the pixel-values of the associated image.

In [16]:
### Confusion Matrix
def plot_confusion_matrix(conf_matrix, ax):
    norm_conf_matrix = conf_matrix.astype('float') / conf_matrix.sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)
    np.fill_diagonal(norm_conf_matrix, 0)
    sns.heatmap(norm_conf_matrix, ax=ax, annot=False, cmap="coolwarm", fmt='.0f')
    for i in range(len(conf_matrix)):
        for j in range(len(conf_matrix)):
            plt.text(j+0.5, i+0.5, conf_matrix[i][j], ha='center', va='center')
    plt.title('Confusion matrix')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
In [17]:
### Classification Report
def plot_classif_report(clf_report, ax, vmin=0.93, vmax=1):
    mask1 = np.zeros_like(clf_report, dtype=bool)
    mask1[10:, :] = True
    mask2 = np.zeros_like(clf_report, dtype=bool)
    mask2[:10, :] = True
    cmap_white = ListedColormap(['white'])
    sns.heatmap(clf_report, ax=ax, mask=mask1, annot=True, cmap='viridis', fmt='.6f', vmin=vmin, vmax=vmax, cbar=False)
    sns.heatmap(clf_report, ax=ax, mask=mask2, annot=True, cmap=cmap_white, fmt='.6f', cbar=False)
    ax.set_title("Classification report", fontsize=10, pad=10)
    ax.xaxis.tick_top()
    ax.xaxis.set_label_position('top')
In [18]:
### Evaluation Report
def print_eval_report(y_actual, y_predicted):
    # accuracy score print
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_actual, y_predicted)
    print('Accuracy: {:.4f}%'.format(accuracy*100))
    # confusion matrix
    conf_mx = confusion_matrix(y_actual, y_predicted)
    classif_report_df = pd.DataFrame(classification_report(y_actual, y_predicted, output_dict=True)).iloc[:-1, :].T
    fig,(ax0, ax1) = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,5), sharex=False, gridspec_kw={'width_ratios': [1, 2.2]}, dpi=100)
    # call functions to classification report and confusion matrix plots
    plot_classif_report(classif_report_df, ax0)
    plot_confusion_matrix(conf_mx, ax1)
    fig.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Reported accuracy of the best model {'model': SVC(), 'scaler': MinMaxScaler()} constructed from the GridSearch is 96.7524%, which is quite high, but will still be tried to fine tune using PCA and hyperparameter tuning.

From the analysis above, we have seen that the SVM with a kernel function is the most powerful classification algorithm, however, to achieve better performance on SVC model, there are several improvements that can be applied:

  • PCA: Apply PCA (Principal Component Analysis) or other dimensionality reduction techniques to reduce the number of features without losing too much information.
  • Hyperparameter Tuning: Optimize the regularization parameter (C) to control the trade-off between overfitting and underfitting. A smaller C value creates a wider margin, allowing for more misclassifications but better generalization. A larger C value creates a narrower margin, reducing misclassifications at the cost of potentially overfitting the model. For the RBF kernel, optimize the gamma parameter, which determines the shape of the decision boundary. A low gamma value produces a more flexible decision boundary, while a high gamma value produces a more rigid decision boundary. Use techniques like Grid Search or Randomized Search to find the optimal combination of hyperparameters.
  • Kernel Selection: Experiment with different kernel functions, such as linear, polynomial, Radial Basis Function (RBF), and sigmoid, to find the one that works best for your dataset. RBF is commonly used with good results, but it's always a good idea to test other options.

Hyperparameter Tuning of SVC¶

Now, hyperparameter tuning will be applied to SVC to see if the model performance is increased. In PCA evaluation, I have used GridSearchCV, which took a long time to process the results. In this analysis, I will utilize HalvingGridSearchCV package.

HalvingGridSearchCV is a great alternative to GridSearchCV when it comes to reducing the computational burden of hyperparameter tuning. It is an implementation of the successive halving algorithm, which is designed to find good hyperparameter combinations more quickly.

In [31]:

        'model__kernel': ['linear', 'rbf'],

Conclusion & Future Improvements¶

The evaluation report above shows that the test accuracy is 97.8857% and the validation accuracy is 0.9810. Using an SVC (C=10, gamma=0.01) with a model kernel of 'rbf', PCA(n_components=50), and a MinMaxScaler, model proved to be the best performing in terms of f1 score.

The confusion matrix shows that the highest misclassification is with number 3 being mislabeled as 2 and number 9 being mislabeled as 4, with both 23 misclassifications.

Overall, the testing and validation accuracies are quite high both close to 98 %. Using hyperparameter tuning, PCA and GridSearch, the best model was developed and tested.

Future improvements might include:

  • Data Augmentation: Data augmentation is a method that slightly alters the training data in order to create more training samples with correct labels, which can be further used to train a more comprehensive model that can be more accurate.
